h3. Summary

Some users are receiving repeatedly notifications for resolved requests with changed issue types.
h3. Environment

Cloud + Classic project
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Go to Project Settings -> Customer Notifications;
 # Edit the customer notification for Request Resolved;
 # In the content of the Request Resolved notification, add the field {{$\{request.status}}} and save;
 # In Project Settings -> Language support;
 # Create a new translation for the same notification but without the {{$\{request.status}}} variable;
 # Raise a request;
 # As an agent, change the issue type of the request (this will leave the issue with an invalid Request type), see attached image (screenshot-1) for what this looks like in old issue view;
 # Add 2 customers as participants, each one with a different language that the notification has translations for;
 # Trigger the customer notification by resolving the issue.

h3. Expected Results

Both customers should receive just 1 notification when the request is resolved.
h3. Actual Results

The customer using the language without the customised translation with ${request.status} will receive 21 notifications regarding the resolved request.
h3. Workaround

To temporarily solve the problem, remove any ${request.status} field out of the content of any customer notification for Request Resolved.

h3. Summary
 * Cannot create a cloud mailbox in a service desk project if the name contains dash "-"
 !Screenshot 2019-06-18 at 8.25.26 PM.png|thumbnail! 
 * The following error is reported:
{noformat}
 Invalid email address. Use letters, numbers, periods and underscores.
{noformat}

h3. How to Replicate
 # Navigate to any service desk project on your test instance > Project Settings > Email request 
 # For *Cloud email address* click on edit to update the mailbox email address
 # Mention an email containing a hyphen (dash)

h3. Investigation Done
 * Do not see any error reported in Splunk logs
 *  Following error is reported in the Developer console
{noformat}
{"success":true,"validationErrors":null,"message":null,"code":0}
{noformat}
 * The following bug was raised a long time ago: [https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSDCLOUD-5092] and its related internal ticket "https://hello.atlassian.net/browse/HPT-4517?oldIssueView=true"
 which says that it was because our mailstore uses regex to validate the email address and that the underscore and dash are now included. However, the ticket is very old.
 * Raised a request [https://hello.atlassian.net/browse/MSG-332] and they responded follows:
{quote}yesterday

We no longer validate the mailbox name in Vertimail (the incoming email service). We only validate the domain name.

The error you’re describing sounds like Jira doing validation on the local-part (mailbox name). This is completely self-contained within Jira these days so you’ll need to speak to the Jira Cloud team.
{quote}
* Further the regex currently used to [validate e-mail address|https://stash.atlassian.com/projects/SD/repos/servicedesk-pre-fork/browse/project-ui/src/main/resources/servicedesk/internal/project/pages/incoming-email/emailsettings/email-settings-split-view.js#179] still seems to treat hyphen as invalid. {code:javascript}                if (alias.match(/[^\w.]/)) {
                    this._showErrorMessage({
                        errors: [{errorMessage: AJS.I18n.getText("sd.email.invalid.email.address")}]
                    });{code}
 !Screenshot 2019-06-18 at 7.13.17 PM.png|thumbnail! 
Underscores are however accepted.

h3. Workaround
None available at present.

h3. Summary

Next-gen workflows cannot be saved due to inconsistency on statuses after changing the default language of the site.

h3.Steps to reproduce

# Create a new instance;
# Create a next-gen project;
# Rename the "Done" status to its corresponding Spanish translation: "Listo";
# Change the instance language to Spanish;
# Create a new Request Type. Make sure that it has the "Listo" status on it.

h3. Expected results

The workflows can be changed and saved.

h3. Actual result

The workflow cannot be saved and the error below is shown on the console:
{code}
message: "Status name [listo] must be case-insensitively unique but is being shared between statuses <status ID>, <status ID>"
{code}

h3. Workaround

In order to fix the workflows and save it with the correct statuses, follow the steps below:
# Rollback the instance to English;
# Access the problematic workflows;
# Add the "Listo" status and recreate the transitions;
# Remove the "Done" status;
# Save the workflow;
# Rollback the instance to Spanish.

h3. Summary

App vendor has a Cloud customer that was using an Automation for Jira rule to add internal comments to about 128 issues.  For 126 issues this worked fine, but there were 2 issues where the comment was showing up as public.  The vendor sent exactly the same request for all 128 issues to add comments (we're just looping over a list).

They've confirmed from their logs that they correctly set the "sd.public.comment" property to false.

One comment where shows "jsdPublic":true in the JSON) - exact request added as internal comment

But when comment's entity properties is accessed:
{code}
{
"key":"sd.public.comment"
"value":{
"internal":true
}
}
{code}

Further investigation in splunk suggests that this might be caused by {{PSQL_TOO_MANY_CONNECTIONS}}:
{code}
msg:     java.sql.SQLException: PSQL_TOO_MANY_CONNECTIONS Exception already occurred in this workcontext, skipping next getConnection. Listener: com.atlassian.servicedesk.plugins.onboarding.gettingstarted.intro.GettingStartedRequestIntroIssueEventListener event: com.atlassian.jira.event.issue.IssueEvent
{code}

h3. Notes
* I haven't personally replicated this on my end
* More information found in https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/browse/DEVHELP-2866
